
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dir` mesle dastoor `ls` amal mikonad, yani file-ha va pooshe-ha ra dar yek directory namayesh midahad. Dar vaghe, `dir` bishtar dar system-haye Windows estefade mishavad, vali dar UNIX/Linux niz mojud ast va haman kare `ls` ra anjam midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `dir /b`  --> 🍃 Faqat esm-haye file-ha va pooshe-ha ra namayesh midahad (bedune etela'at ezafi).
    🔹 `dir /a`  --> 👀 Namayesh hameye file-ha, hata anha ke makhfi hastand ya atribute khass darand.
    🔹 `dir /s`  --> 📂 File-ha ra dar hameye zirpooshe-ha ham search va namayesh midahad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dir

    🔹 Namayesh file-ha va pooshe-ha dar directory فعلی.

    $ dir /b

    🔹 Namayesh list sade file-ha va pooshe-ha.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dir /a

    🔹 File-haye makhfi (ke esm-haye aan ba "." shoru mishavad) ham namayesh dade mishavand.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dir` command is similar to the `ls` command; it lists files and directories in a specified directory.  `dir` is primarily used in Windows systems, but it also exists in UNIX/Linux and performs the same function as `ls`.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `dir /b`  --> 🍃 Displays only the names of files and directories (without extra information).
    🔹 `dir /a`  --> 👀 Show all files, including hidden ones or those with specific attributes.
    🔹 `dir /s`  --> 📂 Searches and displays files in all subdirectories as well.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dir

    🔹 Displays files and directories in the current directory.

    $ dir /b

    🔹 Displays a simple list of files and directories.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dir /a

    🔹 Hidden files (whose names start with ".") are also displayed.
